doctype html
html(lang="en")
  head
    title="NewbCSS"
    link(rel="stylesheet", href="https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/font-awesome/4.5.0/css/font-awesome.min.css")
    link(rel="stylesheet", href="dist/css/newb.css")
  body.page
    main
      h1 Welcome to NewbCSS
      p Intro and description
      h2 Philosophies
      section.container
        h4 CSS3
        p.
          I have no real interest in using backwards and broken technologies. My focus is to try to make this lib as simple as possible using current technologies, so if you need <= IE9 you may need to look elsewhere.
        h4 Icons
        p.
          I've included #[a(href="https://fortawesome.github.io/Font-Awesome/", target="_blank") Fontawesome] because it is a great library with tons of beautiful icons. 'Nuff said.
        h4 Accessibility
        p.
          I'm learning about and experimenting with Accessibility. I'll try to improve where I can, as much as I can.
        h4 Support
        p.
          At this point, I'm much more interested in learning and creating than maintaining this as a project proper. That said, feel free to fork, add and remove, and submit a PR to see if that's something that others might also benefit from.
      h2#buttons Buttons
      section.container
        h3 #[code .btn]s
        button.btn DEFAULT
        button.btn.green GREEN
        button.btn.blue BLUE
        button.btn.red RED
        button.btn.grey GREY
        button.btn.orange ORANGE
        button.btn.yellow YELLOW
        button.btn.pink PINK
        a.btn.blue(href="#") BLUE LINK
      section.container.bg.dark
        h3 #[code .dark.btn]s
        button.btn.dark.white WHITE
        button.btn.dark.green GREEN
        button.btn.dark.blue BLUE
        button.btn.dark.red RED
        button.btn.dark.grey GREY
        button.btn.dark.orange ORANGE
        button.btn.dark.yellow YELLOW
        button.btn.dark.pink PINK
      section.container
        h3 #[code .solid.btn]s
        button.btn.solid.upper default
        button.btn.solid.blue.upper blue
        button.btn.solid.red.upper red
        button.btn.solid.green.upper green
      section.container
        h3 #[code .round.btn]s
        button.btn.round ROUND
        a(href="#").btn.round.blue ROUND BLUE ANCHOR
      section.container
        h3 #[code .btn] sizes
        button.btn.sm .btn.sm
        button.btn DEFAULT
        button.btn.lg .btn.lg
        button.btn.xlg .btn.xlg
        p.
          Looking for a smaller button? That might be too small to be tapable...
          But if you're just going for the look, check out #[a(href="#badge") Badges].
      h2#links Links
      section.container
        p: a(href="#") Anchor
        button.link Button as a link
        p Links inside text will be #[a.link underlined] so that they sound out.
      h2#alerts Alerts
      section.container
        h3 #[code .alert]s
        .alert(role="alert") They are transparent by default.
        .alert.green(role="alert") They should be used to provide information. Green may or may not be equated with success messages.
        .alert.blue(role="alert"): p Blue could be informational messages that are not critical. Maybe add a link for #[a.link more information].
        .alert.yellow(role="alert") Yellow is usually used for issues that do not require immediate action.
        .alert.red(role="alert") Red can be the most 'serious' of alerts.
        section.container.bg.dark
          .alert.white(role="alert") Neutral info. Like something about how about cookies are used for your website...
        h3 #[code .solid.alert]
        .alert.solid(role="alert") Lorem ipsum something.
        .alert.green.solid(role="alert") Good job! You did something!
        .alert.blue.solid(role="alert") Just so you know, something happened but it's whatevs.
        .alert.yellow.solid(role="alert") Uh-oh, something might be happening.
        .alert.red.solid(role="alert") Attention: something definitely happened.
        .alert.white.solid(role="alert") To alert or not to alert? That is the question.
        h3 #[code .alert] with #[code .bg]
        .alert.blue.bg.light(role="alert") "HEY! Listen!" ~ Navi, Legend of Zelda
        .alert.yellow.bg.dark(role="alert") "HYYAAAAAAHHHHH!" ~ Link, Legend of Zelda
        h3 #[code .slim.alert]
        .alert.blue.slim(role="alert") Maybe not? It looks like a really long button that doesn't do anything on hover...
        h3 #[code .dismissable.alert]s
        .row
          .col.lg50
            .alert.blue.dismissable(role="alert")
              p You can close this alert.
          .col.lg50
            .alert.solid.red.dismissable(role="alert")
              p You can close this alert. Note the alternate close button style; it is because this is a solid alert.
      h2 Forms
      section.container
        .row
          .col.lg20
            h3 Simple Input
            p: input
          .col.lg20
            h3 Text area
            p: textarea
          .col.lg20
            h3 Dropdowns
            select
              option Option 1
              option Option 2
              option Option 3
              option Option 4
              option Option 5
        .row
          h3 Checkboxes
          .col.lg20
           input(type="checkbox", id="chkbx1")
           label(for="chkbx1") Simple Checkbox
          .col.lg20
           input(type="checkbox", id="chkbx2", checked, aria-checked="true")
           label(for="chkbx2") Prechecked Box
          .col.lg20
           input.slider(type="checkbox", id="chkbx3")
           label(for="chkbx3") Slider checkbox

          .col.lg20
           input.toggle(type="checkbox", id="chkbx4")
           label(for="chkbx4") Toggle checkbox
         .row
           .col.lg100
             p Remember to always associate labels with their inputs using #[code for="checkboxIdName"]
      h2 Tables
      section.container.grid
        .row
          .col.lg33.sm100
            table.table
              thead
                tr: th Standard table
              tbody
                tr: td Row 1
                tr: td Row 2
                tr: td Row 3
                tr: td Row 4
                tr: td Row 5
                tr: td Row 6
          .col.lg33.sm100
